nstructed as problematic and in need of intervention in the Irish State, and considers the strategies, discourses and technologies involved in the art of governing health in advanced liberal democracies. Bringing together academics from social policy, sociology, political science and public health, the text seeks to develop a dialogue about both the nature of health and health policy in the Ireland, but also how governmentality, as a theoretical approach, can contribute to the development of critical health policy analysis.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHealth planning. 0aMedical policyxIrelandxIreland. 0aMedical policyzIreland. 0aMedical policy. 0aNational health services. 0aPublic healthxIreland. 0aPublic healthzIreland. 7aHEALTH & FITNESS / Health Care Issues.2bisacsh  aDisability Act 2005.  aIreland.  aIrish State.  aIrish public health promotion.  aIrish society.  aJean Jacques Rousseau.  aUniversal Health Insurance.  aageing.  abiosocialism.  achild fatness.  acritical social theory.  agovernmentality.  ahealth inequalities.  ahealth policy.  ahealth problems.  amarket-based model.  amental health.  anormative political theory.  apost-Foucauldian ideas.  asmoking.1 aChambers, Derek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDukelow, Fiona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, Claire, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFernandez, Eluska, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFernández, Eluska, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoughnane, Cliona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’Donova